<p>The interview begins with Steve and John attempting to give a primer on Game Theory. Weâ€™ve all heard something like this before, no doubt. Itâ€™s actually not that clear of an explanation.</p>

<p>The showâ€™s producer, [Morgan Levy]{https://morganlevey.com/}, steps in to clarify. (Iâ€™m paraphrasing slightly here.)</p>

<p><em>The Prisonerâ€™s Dilemma is a hypothetical scenario in Game Theory. Imagine Steve and Morgan are in custody for jointly committing a crime. The evidence the police have is weak. The are arrested at the same time and taken to separate holding cells at a police station</em></p>

<p><em>The police explain to Morgan that their are four possible outcomes to the current situation and the Morganâ€™s outcome will depend on what she chooses to do and what Steve, separately, chooses to do.</em></p>

<p>*Two more key pieces of information are: Steve and Morgan cannot talk to each other. Morgan has only two courses of action - Rat Out on Steve, or Stay silent.</p>

<p>The joint scenario set looks like this:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Morgan Ratâ€™s on Steve. Steve stays silent. In this case, Morgan is Defecting on her partnership with Steve. Morgan walks free. Steve goes to jail for 20 years.</li>
  <li>Neither party Ratâ€™s Out on the other. Both parties are cooperating with each other. As the evidence is weak, both are sentenced to 1 year of jail time.</li>
  <li>Both Steve and Morgan Rat Out on each other. Both go to jail for 10 years, a lower sentence as a reward for testifying against each other.</li>
  <li>Steve Ratâ€™s Out on Morgan. He walks free. Morgan gets 20 years in prison.</li>
</ol>

<p><em>Whatâ€™s the best course of action for Morgan?</em></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>John explains: Each party is better of Defecting, double crossing the other, acting on their own interest only. But of <em>both</em> of them do that, the both end up worse off as a result.
From a Game Theory perspective, Defection is called a Dominant Strategy, meaning itâ€™s the best strategy, no matter what the other party does.</p>

  <p>If the other guy Cooperates (stays silent), you can exploit their cooperation by Defecting. If the other party Defects, then youâ€™d be a sucker to Cooperate.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>John goes on to point out that these kinds of scenarios (which Iâ€™ve heard many times before), describe the situation where the Game is Played only Once. The emphasis on <strong>once</strong> is where the term Dilemma is earned.</p>

<h2 id="steve-sums-up">Steve sums up</h2>

<p><em>So, this scenario describes a situation where the best thing we could do is Cooperate. But, since our private incentives get in the way, so we canâ€™t do that. We left stuck at the only other outcome - we Both Defect, and end up with a pretty bad outcome, but not as bad as if we were made the Sucker by the Other.</em></p>

<h2 id="the-set-of-all-games">The Set of All Games</h2>

<p>This podcast took me to new places in terms of game theory by distinguishing this hypothetical single-pass game from the far more common human experience ofâ€¦behaviours that arise over time in circumstances that repeat, at least partially.</p>

<p>John: <em>The original analysis I read when I was 17 said, if you know when the game is going to end, you are better of Defecting right from the beginning. If you <strong>donâ€™t</strong> know when the game is going to end, you can use the history of the game to update your strategy.</em></p>

<p>Steve: <em>â€œIf you play the game over and over, you can use the future rounds to Punish the other party if the Defect on you now. You are demonstrating to the other, â€œIâ€™ll cooperate with you, as long as you donâ€™t Defect on me.  Over time, a Game-Theoretical Equilibrium can arise as both parties learn to exploit the benefits of Cooperationâ€</em></p>

<p>John: <em>â€œI call that the Shadow of the Future, the idea that the Future can effect what youâ€™re doing now.â€</em></p>

<h2 id="the-repeated-prisoners-dilemma-tournament">The Repeated Prisoners Dilemma Tournament</h2>

<p>John had ran a contest based on Computerised Chess Tournaments. He involved 13 academic researches who each submitted a codified or algorithmic solutions to the Repeated Prisonerâ€™s Dilemma. John collected results over a number of iterations of this Tournament approach, and found the following â€˜winningâ€™ strategiesâ€™.</p>

<h3 id="insights">Insights</h3>

<p>None of the submissions included to the two most simple and obvious strategies. Always Cooperating or Always Defecting lead to the <em>worst</em> set of pay-offs.</p>

<p>Reciprocity (or Tit for Tat) was far and away the most successful strategy found in the Tournament(s). The summary, from John is:</p>

<p><em>â€œTit for Tat - A player Cooperates on the First move. Then does what the other â€˜playerâ€™ does on each subsequent moveâ€</em></p>

<p>What you are communicating is:  <em>â€œIâ€™m willing to Cooperate if you are. If youâ€™re not, Iâ€™m going to Defect. Iâ€™m just gonna Echo what you do. Hopefully you realise that you are better off Cooperating with me, then Iâ€™ll Cooperate the next time. Then we can bother do pretty wellâ€</em></p>

<p>John goes on to give explanations of tragic strategic failures - the worst of which, is Massive Retaliation or the Grim Reaper strategy. This is when a â€˜playerâ€™ responds to Defection by <em>always</em> Defecting, getting their â€˜paybackâ€™ over and over. Does this remind you of anyone you know?</p>

<p>John finds himself stuck for words other than Nice or â€˜Nicenessâ€™ to describe a key element of a successful strategy. This is to signal to the other â€˜playerâ€™ of youâ€™re preparedness to Cooperate. There is a corresponding â€˜Not-Niceâ€™ with the opposite level of success in the Tournament.</p>

<p>The Tournament was won by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anatol_Rapoport">Anatole Rappaport</a>, who liaised with John after the tournament, reminding him that this thought experiment would have a poor representation in Daylight Life, due to the immense complexity of human behaviour in â€˜the Wildâ€™.</p>

<p>The key findings from the tournament are, in order:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Be Nice. Keep Cooperating as long as the â€˜other guy doesâ€™. Donâ€™t â€˜start troubleâ€™</li>
  <li>Be forgiving. Leaning into â€˜paybackâ€™ or â€˜punishmentâ€™ will cost you as a strategy.</li>
  <li>Be provokable. If youâ€™re a â€˜suckerâ€™ all the time, you are setting yourself up for exploitation from â€˜the other guyâ€™</li>
</ol>

<p>Why so many quoted â€˜other guysâ€™ and â€˜other playersâ€™ in my writing above? Here, Iâ€™m paying credence to Johnâ€™s advice through the interview. Be careful of Zero Sum thinking. There is no room for â€˜opponentsâ€™ in successful Game Theoretical Strategy. In Johnâ€™s experience, there are almost zero real life examples of Zero Sum situations in life - â€œSports and Warfareâ€ are about the only two.</p>

